<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06042123 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06042123 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PALO-ALTO; POLICE; PROBE; LODGING; BUILDING; ROBBERY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Dozens of Palo Alto police officers -- including a SWAT team -- shut down ahotel Sunday as they searched for two men suspected of burglarizing a room.;   About 50 officers cordoned off the Holiday Inn on El Camino Real about 11:30a.m. and prevented guests from entering or leaving the hotel, Officer JeanKrahulec said. They searched room-to-room for the two men, reported to havestolen a piece of luggage Sunday morning.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HOTEL AT STANDSTILL WHILE P.A. POLICE HUNTPAIR OF THIEVES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The hotel remained sealed off in early evening. Police, who said theirsearch could take several hours, reported no injuries although one of the menwas believed to have a gun.;    Police said the two men entered Room 327 about10 a.m. while a maid was cleaning the room. One man grabbed her by the wristand pushed her into a corner while the other picked up the luggage.;    Whilepolice were at the hotel, another employee reported seeing a man with a guntucked into his belt running through a hallway. Officers from Palo Alto's SWATteam arrived at about 1 p.m.;    Hotel employees called each of the estimated150 guests at the 282-room hotel, warning them to lock their doors and stay intheir rooms as police began searching for the burglars.;    Other guests whohad been locked out of their rooms congregated at a nearby bar, where arrivingguests also were taken.;    Patrick Siles, front desk manager at the hotel,said at least one guest missed a flight to Mexico when he could not return tohis room to retrieve his luggage.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RODNEY FOO, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910211  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.